We most fre- quently read, however, of bullae as ornaments suspended from the necks of children, and worn especially by the sons of the noble and wealthy. Such a youth is called hoeres bullatus (Sat. 14. 4.) The bulla was worn by children of both sexes as a token of paternal affection and a sign of high birth. Instead of the bulla of gold, boys of inferior rank, including the children of freedmen, wore only a piece of leather. On arriving at adolescence the bulla was laid aside, together with the prae- tea-ta, and it was often consecrated, on this occasion, to the Lares, or to some divinity. Many consider that the bulla was formed of a pecu- liar shape, in order to atti-act the gaze of the passenger, and avert urentes oculos.
